observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, in coordination of the Human Resource Management Officer:
Formulate and adopt written Internal Policy Guidelines on hiring of personnel under Job Order (JO);
Secure a prior authorization from the Sangguniang Bayan to enter into a contract with the JO Workers;
Ensure the adoption of the mandated daily minimum wage rate of the JO Workers as mandated by the Regional Tripartite Wages and Productivity Board;
Fill in the vacant Plantilla positions and/or create the mandatory positions as provided under CSC MC No. 12 series of 2022, subject to the prescribed PS limitation, to perform the functions of a regular/permanent employee in order to minimize the hiring of JO workers.

We recommended that the Human Resource Management Officer and the Municipal Accountant:
diligently withheld the billed amount and the mandatory contributions from the employee’s salary and immediately remit the same to the Pag-IBIG;
conduct a thorough verification, analysis and validation of the individual accounts under the Due to Pag-IBIG account;
reconcile the negative balances and/or substantiate the balances, including the recognition of the necessary adjustments, as warranted; and
coordinate with concerned employees with Reminder Notice to settle the arrearages to avoid the accumulation of penalties.

We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer, in coordination of the Municipal Budget Officer, submit the following certified statement to the LSB not later than July 15 of the current year, to wit:

a. Actual SEF Income for the immediately preceding fiscal year;

b. Actual SEF Income for the first two quarters of the current year;

c. Estimated SEF Income for the two quarters of the current years; and

d. Annual Estimates for the ensuing year.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer:
conduct a periodic reconciliation between the books of accounts and cashbook at least every quarter;
prepare the necessary adjustments for both the books of accounts and cashbook for all identified reconciling items.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor monitor the complete implementation of all programs, projects and activities funded by the National Agencies, as stated and agreed in the Memorandum of Agreement (MOA).
We also recommended that the implementing Department Heads:
retrieve all MOA or any related documents to determine the specific purpose of each fund received from the National Agencies;
implement the programs, projects and activities for the intended purpose within the timelines agreed; and
initiate a written formal request with the Source Agencies to allow the LGU to further utilize the fund, especially those Agencies with Demand Letters.
Further, we recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
exhaust all efforts and remedies to determine the specific details on the balances of the Due to NGA account;
maintain a Subsidiary Ledger for each fund received from the National Agencies; and
examine the noted discrepancies on the reported balances, and the determination of the detail of the program/projects and activities for each Source Agencies, including the preparation of necessary adjustments to correct the balances.
Lastly, we recommended that the Municipal Treasurer:
retain a copy of the MOA on all funds received from any Source Agencies;
return all unexpended balance or excess funds to the source agency;
return all idle funds with the Bureau of Treasury for those funds with undeterminable Source Agency and/or its specific purpose, only after all efforts and remedies are exhausted.

We recommend that the Municipal Mayor to:
Create an Inventory Committee, who will be temporarily relieved of all their regular duties, to conduct the complete physical inventory in three (3) months or less;
Require the Inventory Committee to prepare a Physical Inventory Plan and the submission of a copy to the COA Audit Team, at least ten (10) calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory-taking activities; and
Supervise the conduct of the physical count and the immediate preparation of a Report on Physical Count of PPE using the prescribed form and the submission of the report to the Audit Team;
Initiate the implementation of all prior years’ audit recommendations on PPE account, as well as, the full implementation of “One-time cleansing of PPE accounts” as provided in COA Circular No. 2020-006; and ;
Consider the appointment of a General Services Officer (GSO) who shall take charge of property management.

We also recommend that the Municipal Accountant to correct the erroneous entry on Land account and recognize the issued items as discussed in paragraphs 1.8 to 1.10.

We recommend further, that the Property Officer issue the necessary Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) for the procured items below the ₱15,000.00 capitalization threshold for PPE.

We recommend that the Municipal Treasurer:

prepare monthly a report of unpaid accounts;

submit to the Municipal Accountant the monthly Billing Statements of Water Consumers;

prepare Demand Letters to all delinquent water consumers; and

impose penalties to delinquent water consumers, if warranted. 

We recommend that the Municipal Accountant record in the books of accounts the receivables from Waterworks System based on the report of unpaid accounts prepared by the Municipal Treasurer and provide for the necessary allowance for doubtful accounts.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor issue a directive to all department heads mandating the following:

 14.) Maintain a logbook to record all supplies requisitioned, consumed and utilized and with month-end balances of remaining stocks on hand;

15.)Submit a report of stocks on hand every June 30 and December 31 each year to the designated Property Officer for consolidation; and

16.) Submit to the Municipal Accountant the Distribution Lists or proof of actual receipt by the intended recipients of the goods procured for a particular program.


We also recommended that the designated Property Officer:

17.) Prepare a pre-numbered Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) for every supplies issued to be signed by the Head of each requisitioning office and summarize all RIS per month by preparing the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) monthly;

 18.)Submit to the Municipal Accountant every 5th day of the following month the SSMI, supported with the RIS, as basis in recording the issuances as deductions in the Inventory account;

 19.) Prepare a Report on Physical Count of Inventories every June 30 and December 31 each year based on the report of stocks on hand from each office and submit to the Municipal Accountant and to COA not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year; and

 20.) Maintain an updated and complete Stock Cards and reconcile with accounting records monthly.

Further, we recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

 21.) Record supplies and materials under the appropriate Inventory account upon purchase and provide a sub-account for goods issued by the Property Officer to Heads of Offices for implementation of programs;

 22.)Record the equivalent expense only when supported with SSMI or Distribution Lists from the Heads of Offices who are in charge with particular Programs;

 23.) Maintain an updated and complete Supplies Ledger Cards (SLC) and reconcile the same with the Stock Cards of the Property Officer; and

24.) Reconcile balances of Inventory accounts with the RPCI

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, issue a directive to the following officials to perform the following:

 1.) the Municipal Accountant and the Property Officer, trace back all procurement of PPEs of the LGU and provide a Subsidiary Ledger 
 and Property Card for each specific property owned by the LGU, indicating therein the necessary data as to the date of acquisition, purchase cost, specifications,  among others, and record all subsequent procurement therein;

  2.) the Municipal Accountant and the Property Officer reconcile their respective records with the RPCPPE;












3.) the Inventory Team to prepare and submit a revised consolidated RPCPPE in the prescribed format and indicate all the required information pertaining to the properties being accounted, duly signed by the Inventory Committee and approved by the LCE.  Further, direct the Inventory team to prepare and submit the Inventory Report of Municipal Roads; and,

 4.) the Municipal Engineer to prepare Road Map and submit copies to the Accounting Office and Audit Team.

Further, we recommended that that the Municipal Accountant:

  5.) Reconcile SL balances with the General Ledgers, maintain a GL for each PPE account and ensure that year-end balances in the GLs are accurately reflected in the FS;




  6.) Compute depreciation of each specific property in the PPEs and furnish the Audit Team with a copy thereof every January of each year;




 7.)Maintain a GL for Accumulated Depreciation of each specific property PPE account to provide proof of the reflected amounts;




 8.) Present the Book Value of each PPE accounts and the related Accumulated Depreciation in the Notes to the FS instead of lumpsum.

We also reiterated our previous year recommendation that the Designated Property Officer:

  9.) issue Property Acknowledgement Receipt for every equipment issued to an employee to track the custodians of LGU assets and renew all PAR every after three years to account for any losses.

  10.)mark assets with Property Tags counted during Physical Inventory

